		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/03/no-springtime-renewal-in-the-job-market/" data-title="No Springtime Renewal in the Job Market" data-description="Are Marchâs dismal jobs numbers a fluke, or the start of something bad?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="p1"><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/04/opinion/3tritchWEB2/3tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/04/opinion/3tritchWEB2/3tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/04/opinion/3tritchWEB2/3tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003610888" width="480" height="320" alt="A New York Labor Department office"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A New York Labor Department office</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Spencer Platt/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It will take another few months to see if the unexpectedly dismal job market in March was a fluke or the start of something bad. Economists had expectedÂ <a title="Bureau of Labor Statistics, Apr 3, 2015" href="//www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.nr0.htm" target="_blank">the latest employment report</a>, releasedÂ <span class="aBn" tabindex="0" data-term="goog_272411654"><span class="aQJ">on Friday</span></span>, to show 250,000 newly-created jobs last month, in line with the encouraging monthly tallies in the past year. But the economy added only 126,000 jobs and totals for January and February were revised down by 69,000 jobs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In another sign of weakness, wage growth has remained stuck, at about 2 percent over the past year â a rate that barely outflanks inflation and hasnât budged in five years, even as overall job prospects have improved. To add insult to injury, the length of the workweek ticked down in March, to 33.7 hours on average for most workers. The combination of flat wage growth and fewer hours led to a slight decline last month in average weekly pay.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Those dynamics â basically, uneven job growth plus flat wages â may explain why consumer spending has been lackluster in recent months, despite low prices. The retail sales report for March, dueÂ <span class="aBn" tabindex="0" data-term="goog_272411655"><span class="aQJ">April 14</span></span>, will be an important piece of the puzzle in determining whether the new jobs data reflect the economic drag of winter weather and other transitory factors or retrenchment by employers and, by extension, consumers. Strong sales would not square with weak job conditions. Weak sales, on the other hand, would indicate that larger forces are taking a toll on jobs, including the stronger dollar, falling oil prices and government inaction.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For example, job growth in manufacturing slowed dramatically in the first three months of 2015 compared to the last three months of 2014, presumably a result, at least in part, of the stronger dollar. Similarly, the number of oil-and-gas-related jobs has declined along with oil prices; so far this year, some 30,000 such jobs have been lost, compared with a gain of 41,000 jobs in 2014. Ominously, the number of construction jobs was basically unchanged in March, a finding that could improve with the weather or could signal a slow homebuilding season.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the government sector, the number of jobs declined by 3,000 in March, with losses concentrated at the state level. In all, theÂ <a title="Economic Policy Institute, April 3, 2015" href="//www.epi.org/blog/the-economy-continues-to-pay-the-price-for-austerity/" target="_blank">economy is coming up short</a>Â by 1.8 million public sector jobs, a tally that includes nearly half a million positions that were lost in recent years and never replaced, and 1.3 million jobs that should have been added to keep up with population growth, but were never created. Many of those jobs would have been in teaching and other solidly middle class professions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For policymakers, the message of the March report is clear: It is too soon to say with any confidence that the labor market is firmly on the road to health. That argues for continued delay by the Federal Reserve in raising interest rates. It also argues for many measures that, despite evidence of need, the Republican-controlled Congress refuses to provide, including vastly increased infrastructure spending and a substantial raise in the federal minimum wage.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The weakened labor market situation in March may prove fleeting. But it may not. It would not be the first time in the now nearly six-year old recovery that forward momentum has stalled instead of accelerating. The Fed should proceed cautiously and Congress should act boldly.</p>
	</div>
